			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">You're totally missing the point as to the scale of subscriptions.  If current numbers are ANY indication of things to come, 13$ a month had better get us a lot more.
<br />

<br />
Before they switched to the dot listing system, I recall seeing 2000+ players on even at non peak hours was not uncommon.  Even if we take that as an average spot population and look at it one server at a time, this is an incredible number.  2000 players, even if they played an average of 6 hours a day (which would be very unlikely) would average about 8000 subscriptions.  Now let's just look at that a miniute.  That's 8000x13x12 per year plus an initial fee of 8000x50 for a total of about 1.65 million on the first year off the first server alone that is being paid out by the players (ignoring sales tax).  Every month would be 8kx13=104k in pure subscription fees (that's pure revenue, no middlemen).  That's one helluva operating budget for one server.
<br />

<br />
Ok, let's look at kiriyama's breakdown by the numbers.  At $5 per month in "maintenance" that's 8000x5=40000 in expenses.  Checking the transfer logs, this game averages under 5kbps on upload or download and it's safe to say that it's well under either of those caps per person during regular use.  Still, just to be safe, and assuming that it is at 5kbps, that's 2000... heck, double it so that there's no slowdown during peak hours as well! and you get 20000kbps aka 20mbps.  Covad offers t1 lines for small businesses at $674 per month per 1.5mbps with a 2 year contract with an additional discount on larger amounts and with longer contracts plus a $1126 initial rebate which covers nearly all of the equipment and installation fees.  This'll result in  (20/1.5)x674= about 9k in monthly bandwidth fees for better service than we're going to get.  which leaves 31k left for other maintenance expenses.  Even if they bought $8000 in new servers each month and hired four full time, well paid, $20hr technicians to run for them ($20/hr x 40hr/wk x 4wk/mo x 4techies) that's still only 21k a month.  Which leaves 10k unaccounted for... let's say the 10x10 room they put this stuff in to run ONE server costs $50000 a month to rent... yay...  Oh, and we should give the 4 techies an administrative staff too.  Let's pay them $16hr to make sure they're happy 5k/40hr/4wk/16=2 full time mangerial staff per four techies.  This kind of overflow would be perposterous in any real business.
<br />

<br />
Next on the list is the $3 for the in game "zookeepers".  $3x8000=$24k a month for our local csrs.  Let's make them full time, 40hr/wk x 4/wk = 160hrs, and what the hell, pay them about twice as much as many of the players playing the game $12/hr.  Let's see, that would mean we'd have 24/160/12=12.5 full time net csrs on for each server!  Yeah right.  and do you SERIOUSLY think that's going to stop griefers?
<br />

<br />
Ok, now $2 a month for the programmers?  That's 8kx2=16k a month, or about 16kx12=$192000/yr in salary for full time programmers to continually develope and implement new things into the game, or a little more than 6 game developers at $30000/yr.  For that much we better be able to expect amazing new developements on a monthly basis.
<br />

<br />
Now this last part pisses me off the most.  $3 for "fun factor"?!  Is he saying he'd pay $50 plus tax, and $10 a month for a game that he didn't find had "fun factor"?  We pay the upfront fee to get a "fun" game, and that more than covers all of the development and initial profit for the game.  For the $50+tax we should be able to expect a fun game, we should be able to expect our money's worth!  When someone puts out a crappy game, would you support it by paying $50?  Yes, planet side is fun, but if you actually play planetside for a year at that price, you'll have ended up shelling out more than 206 dollars.  Now is that a fair price for a game?  Is this game really $200 of fun?  Or do you have better places to spend your money?
<br />

<br />
The initial purchase price is set at the same level as single payment products, some of which entailed far more effort and were still very very profitable (and yes, many of them include netcode too, some of them massively multiplayer scalable) so that $13 a month is not there for them to recoup expenses, it's should be covering the operating expenses for the product we just purchased, and be giving us the entertainment we just paid for.  Instead it gets dumped into net profit before taxes.  This is the reason why mmorpgs etc are booming right now, it's perposterously profitable.  There's competition out there, and if this is the final price, I may just have to cancel my preorder and find an alternative.  I'm SURE I won't be the only one.
<br />

<br />
Oh, and just so everyone notes this, it gets MORE profitable with greater numbers of people per server (disproportionately so)</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
